>>ce0293c0-3d17-4bc1-90c7-01f30dad6f80
Not bad. Probably the best ZeroNet reference video I've seen so far.
Hopefully some people will get around to see it.

Ignoring the ZeroNet quirks, seems the setup is simple enough although it might be better to have the content.json-default files in the repository itself to avoid people having to create from scratch or copying from somewhere else.
One thing that you've been better is to use git to create a new repository and configure it to track and pull from the remote branch.
Keeping the local repo updated would be a pain the way you did it.

Here's mirror for people that want to avoid clearnet.
